Okay, Trump voters angry about us holdouts, I‚Äôll make a bet with you. I will hold my nose and vote for Donald Trump next week if and only if the following condition is met: 

Sometime between now and Election Day, Trump mobilizes his supporters to help defeat Amendment 4. Unprompted (meaning a Truth Social post, rally comment, campaign mailing, etc. will qualify, but simply reiterating that he personally is voting no in reply to an interview question will not).

This is a staggeringly low bar to clear‚Äîfar lower than I‚Äôve ever had to even consider whether a Republican nominee could clear. It requires no effort or risk on Trump‚Äôs part, and commits him to no positions he doesn‚Äôt claim to already hold. It simply requires him to tell people who hang on his every word to vote the right way on something important while they‚Äôre already there to vote for him.

It wouldn't change my opinion that he‚Äôll be a terrible joke of a president whose victory will do more harm than good, but it would show that there remains at least some lingering capacity to at least fake some basic regard for one of the core causes of the political party he assumed the responsibility of leading.

But if he can‚Äôt even do that‚Äîif he goes this entire campaign cycle without lifting a finger to help beat back the Left in a vitally important referendum‚Äîit will prove my point that conservatives can no longer count on him to do anything for us unless it just happens to be something he wants to do anyway.

Admittedly, part of why I'm willing to commit to this is that I expect Trump to lose Wisconsin regardless of how I vote, and that I'm certain Trump won't exceed my expectations for him. But again, the fact that a Republican standard-bearer being even mildly pro-life on his own is so unlikely is the point.

So, do we have a deal?
